description: medInt Holdings, LLC is a company at the forefront of delivering products for the radiology community to increase patient safety, improve profitability and maintain compliance. Our platform, Imalogix™, is the industry’s only platform that automatically, comprehensively and objectively monitors radiation dose, workflow, performance and quality. Imalogix™ replaces anecdotal evidence with comprehensive, empirical information that is automatically collected from all of a healthcare organization’s imaging scanners. The product audits all data received using a proprietary set of algorithms and business logic. It provides reports and alerts for outlier conditions, and the ability to drill down to unparalleled detail to reveal the underlying root causes. Our solution is uniquely positioned to empower radiologists, safety officers and operations directors with the tools to monitor, remediate and optimize radiation dose, workflow and staffing needs.

description: PCR Pharmacology and Clinical Research The Pharmacology and clinical research company PCR has been created with the specific purpose of conducting high quality clinical research in Mexico .PCR meets all local and international regulatory requirements. All of PCR´s coordinators and investigators are highly qualified. PCR's coordinators (nurses and physicians) have been trained at active research centers within the United States and Mexico. PCR adheres to the highest standards in clinical research by strictly complying with Good Clinical Practice (GCP) . PCR´s personnel participate in ongoing educational programs both in house and externally. . Indeed, progress notes and case report forms (CRF's) are completed in English. PCR has the ability to utilize the large and untapped population in Mexico to quickly identify appropriate subjects and rapidly enroll them. PCR staff is experienced in conducting all phases of clinical research and capable of filling trials in the following Therapeutic Areas: • Cardio logy I Vascular Diseases • Denta l/ Maxillofacial Surgery • Dermatology • Endocrinology including Diabetes & Obesity • Gastroenterology including Liver Disease • Hematology • Immunology • Musculoskeletal • Nephrology I Urology • Neurology I CNS • Obstetrics I Gyneco logy • Oncology • Ophthalmology • Otolaryngo logy I Ear, Nose & Throat • Pediatrics I Neonatology • Psychiatry I Anxiety and Depression • Pulmonary I Respiratory Diseases • Rheumatology • Women's Health • Devices Critical care / 6 bed intensive care unit Infectology PCR site features the following in-house facilities : • Three fully equipped Research Offices, each one staffed by a study coordinator. • A Clinical Laboratory for sample collection. • A well-trained and efficient Patient Outreach and Recruitment Department. • An Education Department, with in-house training programs. PCR affiliations include: Universidad Autonoma de Queretaro (UAQ) Anahuac University Hospital Médica TEC100

description: Responsible of Synapse's Project and Services Unit (PaS), which manages FP7 and H2020 collaborative research projects and proposals for several stakeholders and customers across Europe. In charge of coaching, training and leading a team of project managers, while driving the implementation of 6 projects with ~37M€ investment with the objective of providing an excellent customer service. Human Resources Management - Coach, mentor, and develop staff, including overseeing new employee onboarding and providing career development planning and opportunities. - Empower PaS members to take responsibility for their jobs and goals. Delegate responsibility and expect accountability and regular feedback. - Lead PaS members to meet the organisation's expectations for productivity, quality, and goal accomplishment. - Maintain transparent communication. Appropriately communicate organisation and individual career development information through department meetings, one-on-one meetings, and appropriate email and regular interpersonal communication. Perform Department Management - Manage the overall operational, budgetary, and financial responsibilities and activities of the department with the support of the financial department. - Plan and implement systems that perform the work and fulfill the mission and the goals of the department efficiently and effectively. - Plan, evaluate, and improve the efficiency of processes and procedures to enhance speed, quality, efficiency, and output. - Establish and maintain relevant controls and feedback systems to monitor the operation of the department. - Manage the preparation and maintenance of reports necessary to carry out the functions of the department. Prepares periodic reports for management, as necessary or requested, to track strategic goal accomplishment.

description: Project Manager at SYNAPSE, company specialised in the management of complex distributed projects. He is directly involved in the following projects: - FP7 SAFEGUARD. Member of the Steering Committee. Responsible of the day-to-day management (leader of the Project Management WP). Co-leader of the dissemination & exploitation activities. - FP7 SEMCARE. Member of the Executive Board and responsible of the day-to-day management of the project. Leader of the dissemination & exploitation activities, including Business Modelling. - FP7 NEOVANC. Member of the Network Management Group. Coordinator of the NeoVanc PMO. Support to the global legal and financial management, and to the communication activities. - ERC-PoC SERE. Member of the Project Board. Involved in the business development strategy of the project results (e.g. brainstorming sessions, market & technology watches, identification of end-users, business planning, investors round). - IMI EMIF. Member of the project PMO, providing support to the Coordinating EFPIA Company (Janssen). He is part of the Communication Task Force, responsible for monitoring and implementing the Project's communication strategy, as well as member of the Sustainability & Business Modelling working group, in charge of devising an appropriate exploitation roadmap for the project results. Other projects he managed: - NEOGENIUS PHARMA. Major medical research project aiming to identify one or more candidates for the treatment of inflammatory pain, and involving three of the leading Spanish pharma companies. - European Medicines Agency (EMA). Three projects aiming at producing effective and reliable information for the on-going safety monitoring of drugs in the European Union. Additionally, he provides consultancy on European projects proposal preparation to Coordinators in Spain, Austria, Netherlands, and the UK, and develops business modelling and sustainability strategies for the projects the company is involved in.

description: • Facilitate the implementation of the International Health Regulations (IHR) in 27 countries around the Mediterranean sea. Analyze the coordination mechanisms for health surveillance between the national system and the points of entry (ports, airports and ground crossings), in four countries. Coordinate the development of WHO global guidelines for reinforcing the role of points of entry in national health surveillance. • Strengthen epidemiological surveillance and response in Central Africa. Assess the national system in Cameroon, DRC and Central African Republic. Improve health surveillance tools and procedures, and coordination/communication mechanisms among surveillance actors nationally and internationally. Support the upgrading of equipment and software for data collection, transmission and analysis. • Design electronic tools for health surveillance systems in resource-limited contexts. Liaise with users and software developers, organize in-house tests and field tests, write standard operating procedures. • Coordinate epidemiology courses for high level staff. Assess training needs of health surveillance staff nation-wide in Morocco. Design and carry out a survey among all surveillance workers, plus site visits. Publish results. Convene government authorities around a national strategy for strengthening the surveillance workforce. • Analyze data and write a report on the feasibility of quality management systems for epidemiological surveillance worldwide. Contribute to writing an e-manual on Monitoring and Evaluation of Surveillance Systems of the European Union (ECDC). • Provide technical support to various projects of the department. Revise epidemiological contents of courses. Carry out data analysis and reporting. Contribute to evaluation, decision-making and planning. • Conduct assessment missions in countries to review the state of implementation of the IHR at national level.

description: • Coordinated projects with key partners in the area of communicable diseases, focusing on malaria, trypanosomiasis and hemorrhagic fevers. Developed technical protocols for epidemiological and clinical studies. Recruited and trained investigators. • Organized field studies. Supervised teams of investigators and data managers. Analyzed and interpreted data from field operations and clinical trials. Wrote scientific reports, published in scientific journals and presented results at conferences and seminars. • Teamed-up with informatics engineers for the design and testing of monitoring and surveillance software. • Provided technical support and training for epidemiological surveillance and for management of humanitarian crises. • Conducted evaluations of health programs in Uganda, Angola and Sudan. • Gave lectures on research and field epidemiology methods in France, Denmark, USA, Tunisia, Uganda, DRC and Guinea Bissau, to audiences including governmental and non-governmental professionals, and university students. • Provided training and technical support to users of the monitoring and surveillance software for trypanosomiasis. • Conducted Ebola fever outbreak investigations (Gulu and Mbarara, Uganda).

description: Senior Program Epidemiologist (Onchocerciasis elimination, Lymphatic Filariasis and Schistosomaisis Control programs). Responsibilities include: (i) Onchocerciasis control/elimination, and Schistosomiasis and Lymphatic Filariasis control program (Africa and the Americas). (ii) guiding country program staff (including Ministries of health and district/regional personnel) in monitoring and evaluating program performance and impact on the disease iii) promoting appropriate operational research, iv) community involvement and ownership of disease control/elimination efforts. (vi)Promoting integration of health programs Achievements: The main achievements so far have been: (a) promoted kinship involvement in community-directed initiatives with a strong gender component; (b) trained program staff in community studies and Epi info program for data handling and analysis in Cameroon, Ethiopia, Nigeria; and Uganda (c) established on-going monitoring in Cameroon, Ethiopia, Nigeria and Uganda; (d) got the African Program for Onchocerciasis Control (APOC) to fund training of many community members per community in onchocerciasis endemic communities to sustain the distribution of ivermectin; (e) studied the phenomenon of sustainability; (f) promoted community-directed interventions approach for control of neglected tropical diseases including malaria, HIV/AIDs and tuberculosis; (g) maintained desired treatment coverage every year, and (h) established the only onchocerciasis elimination programs in Sudan and Uganda in Africa in 2006 and 2007 respectively. Interruption of transmission of onchocerciasis in some areas in Sudan and Uganda; (i) established molecular laboratories in Sudan and Uganda; and establishment of a government supported international committee (Uganda Onchocerciasis elimination expert Advisory Committee) for guiding elimination in Uganda and advising ministry of health of Uganda on onchocerciasis elimination.

description: The responsibilities included: (i) establishing and supporting (financially and technically) community-directed treatment with ivermectin (CDTI) program for onchocerciasis control in 11 districts of Uganda through the established health delivery system; (ii) ensuring cost-efficient delivery systems for community driven ivermectin distribution through operational research and dissemination of the research results; (iii) ensuring timely procurement of adequate ivermectin for onchocerciasis control annually. (iv) monitoring the effectiveness of health workers in their facilitation of CDTI programs; (iv) training district health staff in implementation of data driven interventions. (v) liaising with government, UN agencies such as WHO and NGDOs in ensuring smooth running of the CDTI program in the country; (vi) reporting to the technical Director and the Director for program support both in USA; and (vii) have chaired the NGDOs Coalition in Uganda annually for 7 years. Achievements: Established an effective operational research, monitoring and evaluation mechanism for accessing and improving the performance of community directed Interventions strategy for delivering ivermectin. As a result over 90% of the communities achieved a treatment coverage of at least 90% annually. This approach was adapted as a national policy by ministry of health in 2001 for all health problems requiring the involvement of communities. These included malaria, HIV/AIDS, TB, lymphatic filarialsis, schistosomiasis etc.

description: Responsibilities included: (i) assisting the Ministry of Health in establishing the onchocerciasis control program activities in all endemic districts of Uganda. (ii) complete a map of Uganda showing the distribution of onchocerciasis disease using Rapid Epidemiological Mapping of onchocerciasis (REMO) and Rapid Epidemiological Assessment (REA) methods. (iii) ensuring timely procurement of adequate ivermectin for onchocerciasis control annually. (iv) providing financial and technical support to Ministry of health and districts, NOTF members in Community-directed approaches for onchocerciasis control. (iv) monitoring and evaluating of progress towards onchocerciasis control. (vi) reporting to the RBF Medical Director in UK and Vice-President, Finance and administration in USA and the Ministry of health Uganda. Achievements: A complete rapid epidemiological map of onchocerciasis for Uganda was produced. Over 1.5 million Ugandans from onchocerciasis endemic districts were treated annually. Community-directed approaches that are supported and sustained by communities achieved an annual coverage of at least 90%. The National onchocerciasis control task force with the Non-governmental development organisations (NGDOs) coalition to support onchocerciasis control were as formed.

description: The responsibilities included: (i) Establishment and supervision of about 45 community development projects each with a budget ranging from US $25,000 - 150,000) per year. (ii) Recruitment, training and supervise project staff. (iii) Formulating proposal for new projects as planned, raise funds as per WVI country plan. (iv) Ensuring quality delivery of services and financial management in projects. (v) Conducting monitoring, evaluation and operational research in project areas. (vi) Reporting to the Field Operations Manager. Achievements: Through these projects, over 10,000 orphans were fed, educated, housed and looked after by their communities who previously did not have the capacity to do so. Communities were empowered to construct and maintain their schools and health facilities, improve their water sources, access credit and engage in small-scale businesses as individuals or groups, improve family food and cash crop production, Control and prevent HIV/AIDs, and for the displaced access relief food and other essential supplies. I was involved in raising along with colleagues at least US$ 8million annually for the Uganda office. Raised funds from World Vision, USA, CIDA, Australian government, DFID, and World Bank (for projects approved by the Government (Ministry of Planning and Finance) through proposal writing.

description: The responsibilities included: (i) training young people that have completed their first degrees in various skills as change agents in communities (ii) equipping them with research and writing skills so that they could identify problems, write reports, and formulate proposals as per World Vision Country Strategy. (iii) helping them gain experience required for employment within or outside world vision. (iv) providing relief and rehabilitation services to the disadvantaged after civil strife; (v) improving agricultural production at family level; (vi) improving health through improvement of health facilities and road infrastructure, immunisation, water and sanitation, control of malaria through chemotherapy (vii) improving family housing conditions, and construction of primary schools; and (viii) reporting to the Field Operations Manager, World Vision International (Uganda) Achievements : In this war ravaged area in mid northern Uganda, promoted community directed approaches that resulted into reconstruction of 12 schools, a health facility, and roads. Protection of 60 water spings, drilling of 10 boreholes, improved family based food production in a population of a population of about 40,000 people in area. 10 farmers from this previously poor and hungry population won awards in the national agricultural competitions. Routine immunisation for children and women of childbearing age was organised and carried out by community selected and project trained community members. Immunisation coverage improved from 30% to at least 98% annually. School attendance dramatically improved, and people who could not afford one meal a day, afforded 3 meals a day. Business in agricultural products boomed and this area became a major supplier of simsim, beans, maize, cassava, finger millet and oranges in the country. Raised all the funds required from the Australian Development Cooperation.

description: The responsibilities included: (i) establishing and supervising community-based projects in the Northern part of Uganda. (ii) revamped immunization program through training of health workers, and provision of the cold chain (ii) identifying new projects, formulating and marketing their proposals. (iii) monitoring and supervising progress of the partners supported by OXFAM (iv) representing OXFAM in various fora among NGOs or relevant government departments (v) reporting to the Country Director Achievements: a number of local organisations were supported to improve their capacity and deliver quality services to their target communities. Immunisation coverage in northen Uganda improved. The services included, micro-finance provision for small scale business and disadvantaged communities, delivery of community based health services, agricultural development, women emancipation and many others. I worked with colleagues in OXFAM, Uganda and UK offices, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), Overseas Development Agency (now DFID) to raise the funds that supported the projects.

description: The responsibilities included: (i) identifying fertile and habitable areas and resettling the Karamajong people of N.E. Uganda; (ii) organising and constructing road network in order to move supplies for the resettlement project; (iii) establishing health units, immunization and malaria control programs; (iii) organising the communities and developing their capacity to: (a) identify appropriate locations and constructing schools, health units and water points; (b) carry out routine immunization of children and females of childbearing age; (c) organize and carry out nutritional programs for under 5 year children; (d) organize and supply relief food, seeds and implements to the communities; and (e) ensure good hygiene in the established communities; (iv) provide agricultural information and training services to the community members; (v) monitor progress of the communities and supply information to relevant organisations such as UN World Food Programme, and UNICEF and (vi) report to Country Director. Achievements: Through this work, about 40,000 nomadic people were introduced to agricultural activities with well-developed road, health and education infrastructure. I helped to develop their capacity through community-directed approaches and training so as to improve and sustain their productivity. These communities are still in the area I left them, and are still doing well. I worked with colleagues in OXFAM, Uganda and UK offices to raise the funds that supported this project.

description: Recruited to help develop a more robust SDLC process and build solution that included migration from PVCS to StarTeam SCM tool. Contributed to the design and implementation of systems that supported the software development process. Maintained and administrated SCM tools (StarTeam, CaliberRM, Test Director) and provided support for 300-500 users, which included offshore developers. Responsible for testing and upgrading all new versions of SCM tools. Maintain 10 Windows servers and 1 Linux server running various tools to support the SDLC process. Key Contributions: - Currently in the process of converting 150 Java projects from using Ant to Maven2 with Artifactory acting as the maven repository browser. - Add features and functionality to java open source Build and Deployment software customized to fit the demands of the IT Application Development team. - Developed a Deployed Code Dashboard using Java/HTML and StarTeam Triggered events for the purpose of keeping track of multiple versions of code deployed to various environments. - Developed a real time web based document publication application using StarTeam Tasks and Links that would reflect changes made to a document when a new revision was checked in. - Helped complete and extend Automated Build application built on Java and struts framework. - Converted and optimized ant scripts for each project to be used in the Automated Build solution. - Developed a License Balancer application in Java to help keep costs down by redistributing licenses during off hours to offshore accounts. The License Balancer also prioritized licenses based on user activity in the tool. - Implemented a customized workflow in StarTeam for the change request process that replaced the MS. Outlook form approval process. - Lead all projects to upgrade the SCM tool software which includes writing upgrade plans, installing software on QA machines, testing functionality, scheduling server downtime and implementation.

description: Based at the Enteric Virus Unit, Centre for Infections at the UK Health Protection Agency (now known as Public Health England). I managed a project using the millennium cohort samples, a large longitudinal study on early childhood diseases. The project aims to design ELISA assays to test for common childhood illnesses. This involves protein expression work and using the baculovirus expression system to generate antigens. The project has focused on designing assays that are optimised for oral fluid which allows specimens to be collected from young children.

description: The Kirby Institute for infection and immunity in society was formerly known as the National Centre in HIV Epidemiology and Clinical Research. This position was based in the Centre for Immunology, St Vincent’s Hospital in Sydney, Australia. My work focused on HIV-associated Lipodystrophy project, and investigating Nucleoside Reverse Transcriptase Inhibitor induced mitochondrial toxicity. I was responsible for the majority of laboratory work on a number of clinical trials looking at changes in gene expression in subcutaneous fat biopsies and monocyte samples.

description: Dr Sissoko is currently an independent consultant with more than 10 years experience in Infectious diseases/tropical medicine and epidemiology. Dr. Sissoko’ work interests focus on epidemiological studies design and advanced data analysis, evaluation and adaptation of surveillance programs and health systems research applied mainly to viral infectious diseases (vector-borne infections, HIV/AIDS, Hepatitis B and C) and immunization. He also designs course curriculum and teaches research methods in epidemiology and global health in low and middle income countries.

description: Our aims: 1). Improve our understanding of parasite resistance to the artemisinin class of antimalarial drugs 2). Develop phenotypic and molecular markers of artemisinin-resistant Plasmodium falciparum in Cambodia 3). Identify the parasite genetic determinant of emerging clinical resistance to piperaquine, the partner drug in Cambodia's first-line artemisinin combination treatment (ACT) for P. falciparum malaria 4). Determination of the emergence of multidrug-resistant Plasmodium falciparum in Cambodia

Led staff in the development of Monitoring and Evaluation strategy but also in conducting internal project baseline and review assessments.

description: ZeClinics is a start-up CRO, founded in June 2013. We provide our expertise in the use of zebrafish to pharmaceutical and biotech companies to innovate the preclinical phase of drug discovery. We offer assays of general and organo-specific toxicity and efficacy in the fields of oncology and neural disorders. Besides our interest in pharma industry services, ZeClinics establish partnerships with academic groups interested in using zebrafish in their research & development. As ZeClinics CEO I am responsible of the guide and management of our company vision, strategy and future plan. Moreover as a scientist I closely follow and perform our experimental assays and as co-founder I collaborate in the assessment of our services quality, search for public and private funding and marketing/partnership.

description: PhD in Biomedicine, Neuroscience at the Center for Genomic Regulation, Barcelona Spain. I have studied how pathological fear memories are developed and extinguished in a mouse model of panic disorder. With my work I have contributed to define a novel mechanism related to an unbalanced excitatory/inhibitory system as a potential key factor underlying exaggerated fear memories. With this work we highlighted a putative pathophysiological process in one of the most common psychiatric condition, panic disorder.

description: During my research period in the lab of Stem Cell Research at the Department of Biomedical Engineering I have worked on a project entitled "Characterizing putative neural stem cells harvested from the adult primate brain". During this period I have contributed to the ex-vivo characterization of neural progenitor cells isolated from the hippocampus of adult macaque monkeys. This work has been devoted to redact and present my master's thesis.

description: Contributing in different drug discovery and development research projects (oncology and CNS) and clinical candidate optimization. Assessing pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of ocular implants in healthy and disease animal models. * Designed, optimized desired formulations, pharmacokinetics (PK) and pharmacodynamics (PD) of ocular drug delivery implants. * Planned, designed, developed, validated sensitive analytical methods by HPLC and LC/MS/MS per FDA guidance * Trained junior scientists on method development, validation and sample extraction techniques * Analyzed in vitro release kinetics samples and ocular in vivo pharmacokinetics, pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic, efficacy study samples to include aqueous humor, vitreous humor, cornea, conjunctiva, sclera, iris/ciliary body and retina/choroid. * Extensively worked on analyzing samples from tissue distribution, drug disposition and metabolite identification studies. * Developed, fully validated sensitive, selective methods using LC/MS/MS (per FDA guidance), analyzed, interpreted and communicated results in Oncology, CNS and diabetes research projects. * Used Heidelberg Spectral Domain Optical Coherence Tomography (SD-OCT) to investigate retinal edema and thickness changes, slit lamp biomicroscopy to grade ocular inflammation. * Developed and validated Concanavalin A induced inflammatory uveitic cataract model and studied pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of long term dexamethasone releasing bioerodible ocular implant. * Designed, established proof-of-concept, developed bioerodible dexamethasone implants capable of releasing dexamethasone for 2 and 6 weeks for the treatment of postoperative cataract surgery inflammation and uveitis. • Provided scientific leadership in bio-analysis, pharmacokinetics and pharmacology to drive projects from concept generation to lead optimization * Recognized as the subject-matter expert in pre-formulation, pharmacokinetics, bio-analysis, pharmacodynamics and CMC.

description: * Established proof-of-concept that small, large molecules reach front and back of the eye when injected in to the eye’s lens capsule. * Hands-on experience in developing, validating highly selective and sensitive bioanalytical assays for the quantification of steroids, NSAIDS, BTK and JAK2 inhibitors etc in various biological matrices. * Hands-on experience with Ex Vivo stability in aqueous, SGF (simulated gastric fluid) and SIF (simulated intestine fluid), plasma, serum matrices etc. * Designed, coordinated, and conducted PK and PD studies for several ocular drug delivery implants and other treatment modalities in rabbits. * Hands-on experience with metabolic stability (microsomes, hepatocytes), Red Blood Cell partitioning assays. * Supported several small pharmaceutical companies in the Research Park, Salt Lake City as the key person with in vitro ADME, pre-formulation, PK, bio-analysis, data analysis using Phoenix WinNonlin®, report writing and communicating results with recommendations. * Hands on experience in developing fit for the purpose formulations to study PK in rodents for the early stage discovery compounds. * Hands on experience in titrating dose volumes (using specialized excipients in the formulation) and demonstrated experience in developing recipes for different routes of administration for New Chemical Entities (NCE’s). * Trained volunteers, graduate students in handling experimental animals, formulation strategies, pharmacokinetics, to include dosing, sample collection etc.

description: Worked on collaborative research projects from Novartis, Johnson and Johnson and contributed as a key resource person from DMPK department with aggressive timelines. * Supervised up to 5 MS-level scientists and senior scientists to include hiring, daily workload, scientific trouble shooting, performance reviews etc. in bio-analytical, and in vivo PK arms of DMPK division. * Supported around 6 discovery research projects by addressing all aspects of bio-analytical and formulation issues. * Developed, validated sensitive and selective assays using LC/MS/MS and HPLC to analyze blood, plasma, urine, feces, tissue/organ biological samples for pharmacokinetic, tissue disposition (mass balance), toxicokinetic and PK/PD studies. * Analyzed, interpreted metabolic stability, plasma protein binding, PK, toxicokinetics, dose-range finding studies, PK/PD study outcomes and shared results with recommendations to inter-departmental working groups and senior management team. * Contributed in scaling inter-species preclinical data to project first in human dose by Allometry. * Conducted PK and PK/PD studies in rodents (healthy and disease models to include ZDF rats, ob/ob mouse, db/db mouse and DBA1J mouse models) and mechanistic ADME (absorption, distribution, metabolism and elimination) studies both in vitro and in vivo. * Developed and implemented novel analytical in vitro and in vivo methods to improve compound druggability from DMPK perspective. * Represented DMPK function in early project team meetings and collaborated with CMC, pharmacology, clinical and regulatory groups as necessary. * Authored monthly reports in each project; PK, PK/PD, bioanalytical reports for IND filing. * Supported in identifying CRO's and provided method transfer and validation support. * Received INSTA research award for successful contribution.

description: * Extensively contributed in preclinical profiling and optimization of "New Chemical Entities" in diabetes, inflammation and arthritis research projects. * Supervised 1 MS-level scientist to include daily work load, scientific trouble shooting and performance reviews etc. * Hands-on experience with method development, validation and bio-analysis of pre-clinical and clinical (Phase I and II) study samples by LC/MS/MS and HPLC * Involved in study design, conduct and analysis of in vitro assays to include metabolic stability, plasma protein binding, permeability and CytochromeP450 inhibition and induction studies. * Hands-on experience in designing, coordinating, executing and analyzing PK, PK/PD studies in Beagle dogs. * Involved in designing, conducting in vitro ADME assays and troubleshooting. * Managed laboratory functions including organization, ordering and also coordinating and scheduling MS, PPB, PK, TK, PK/PD studies. * Conducted GLP toxicokinetic/toxicology studies as one of the Study Director. * Hands-on experience with Phoenix WinNonlin Pharmacokinetic software for non-compartmental and compartmental modeling.

description: * Developed class lectures in pharmacology, pharmacokinetics, and human physiology, guided in learning/understanding followed by assessment. * Introduction and overview of pharmacogenomics, how pharmacogenomic variations can affect pharmacokinetic and pharmacological principles. * Role of pharmacogenomics in improving the efficacy of certain drugs or reducing potential adverse events to include regulatory issues * Role of pharmacist in the application of pharmacogenomics at the pharmacist and organization level. * Drug administration (different routes), dose volumes, formulations, absorption, distribution, metabolism and elimination (ADME) characteristics with different types of drugs. * Therapeutic uses of hypnotics, sedatives, local and general anesthetics, duration of action and patient care under sedation. * Member of Curriculum, Planning Priorities and Resources Committee (PPRC). * Conducted research on diabetes and inflammation research projects by involving undergraduate and graduate students.

description: Responsible to the Chief of Defence Personnel as lead for defence welfare policy, including assurance and governance of the Deployed Welfare Package, to deployed military personnel throughout the world. Senior advisor to the Minister of State for Defence Personnel, Welfare and Veterans on all issues regarding operational welfare. Lead Staff Officer for a number of Joint Service Publications, giving direction to the Service community on areas of welfare policy. Policy lead regarding interpretation and arbitration of joint casualty and compassionate support. Policy advisor regarding operational welfare to the Defence Military Crises Centre. Author of the Defence Recovery Capability policy, enabling the transition of wounded, injured and sick Service personnel either to a return to duty, or to a useful life within a civilian environment and special advisor to the Defence Recovery Steering Group. Lead for the Mass Casualty Incident policy for the management of a major incident abroad, involving MoD personnel and their repatriation back to the UK. This includes cross-government briefing up to and including Prime Minister level and liaison with all external agencies, including international embassies and governments. Responsible for the implementation of the Deployed Welfare Package, ensuring Service personnel gain the fundamental elements of welfare; communicate, entertain, connect and support. This required close work with both the contract agencies and the military Permanent Joint Headquarters at Northwood and resulted in an £11M saving.

description: Advised the General Staff on all medical and healthcare issues and contribute at Board level to strategic level planning and organisational management. Provided supervision and direction to the London District Environmental Health Team and to co-ordinate public health proactive & reactive intervention & support. Facilitated the provision of appropriate healthcare, medical policy direction and advice to support military activity in London ensuring reduced manpower wastage and increased operational deployability. Monitored the provision of primary healthcare (GP services and primary dental care) from defence agencies and co-ordinate provision of occupational health to Reservist personnel within the London area. Competent Medical Authority for all medical risk assessments, providing governance and assurance on high-risk recreation and adventure training, overseas training exercises and other hazardous unit activity. Co-ordinated the provision of medical cover to Army Cadet Force/Combined Cadet Force camps within boundaries and occupational health to Adult Instructors. Account holder for the £1.4M London District medical budget. Developed community engagement with the NHS Clinical Commissioning Groups, Local Authorities, emergency planning departments and the Health Protection Agency. Responsible for the planning and execution of medical and healthcare support to all military personnel involved in ceremonial duties, including; Queens Birthday Parade, Garter Service Windsor, Royal Wedding, Diamond Jubilee and the 2012 Olympics. Responsible for the integration of service provision through negotiation and the establishment of contracts to provide emergency medical cover for ceremonial events. This included nurturing cooperation between the military, SO14 of the Metropolitan Police and St John Ambulance.

description: Managed the professional development, technical oversight and quality assurance of 20 full-time technical instructional staff. Planned and prioritised the learning outcomes and training objectives. Supervised the strategic development and implementation of Department of Environmental & Occupational Health policy, in line with Joint Medical Command directives. Supervised the performance measurement and quality assurance of course output. Commanding Officer for all military Environmental Health Technician student cohorts, including annual appraisal and the execution of summarily jurisdiction. Chaired the annual military Environmental Health Technician selection board. Responsible for the fiscal management of the £250k annual departmental training budget. Senior military member of the academic partner board for Middlesex University. Military educational and professional advisor to the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health. Motivated and maximised output and employee morale without financial incentives. Successfully managed organisational change and enhanced higher performance and team productivity during a period of shrinking budgets and increasing workload. Initiated the successful validation of the Military Environmental Health Technician course with Middlesex University to Degree. Initiated the successful accreditation of the Mil Environmental Health Technician course by the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health. Designed the professional career pathway for Mil Environmental Health Practitioners to BSc and full registration with the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health.

description: Research, capacity development and advisory functions focusing on developing countries. His main work has included research on health systems and disease control, coordination of research, capacity development for research and operations as well as research based knowledge management, advisory and consultancy functions. The collaboration with the Danish International Development Agency, the World Health Organization and with a range of other health and health related national and internatinal organizations has been continuous. Specfic areas of work include health management information systems, fairness and accountability in priority setting, public health planning, management and evaluation. Training has included PhD level supervision and development of modules of public health.

description: Research, capacity development and advisory functions focusing on developing countries. His main work has included research on health systems and disease control, coordination of research, capacity development for research and operations as well as research based knowledge management, advisory and consultancy functions. The collaboration with the Danish International Development Agency, the World Health Organization and with a range of other health and health related national and internatinal organizations has been continuous. Specfic areas of work include health management information systems, fairness and accountability in priority setting, public health planning, management and evaluation. Training has included PhD level supervision and development of modules of public health.

description: HERD, the agency I work with, is a Nepalese non-governmental organization specializing in research and monitoring works of various natures in the health and social science sectors. We design and implement large scale national surveys at household and health facility level. Likewise, we conduct program based operational research, baseline, endline and evaluative studies. We have been implementing various studies using wider range of methods: RCTs, action research, operational research, ethnographic studs in understanding various aspects of health interventions. We have a strong research team, qualified both in quantitative and qualitative research studies comprising of public health and social science graduates, ethnographer, economists, medics, educationalists and an experienced operations team to meet the requirement of organizational and research logistics. We have significant partnership with different academic institutions, government agencies and donor communities. We have more than a decade long research partnership with the University of Leeds UK, Nuffield Centre for International Health and Development, operationalising COMDIS-HSD research in several countries. HERD is dedicated to promote research culture in government and non-government organizations, studies and capacity of individuals/institutions in health research sector and consider every new partnership as an opportunity to further our interest in doing so.

description: I have authored or co-authored 31 international peer reviewed publications. Recent papers include: 1. Viljoen J, Tuaillon E, Nagot N, et al. Cytomegalovirus, and possibly Epstein Barr virus, shedding in breast-milk is associated with HIV-1 transmission by breastfeeding. AIDS. (accepted 23 Oct 2014). Presented at the Conference on Retroviruses and Opportunistic Infections (CROI), 3-6 March 2014, Boston, Massachusetts, USA. 2. Kania D, Ottomani L, Meda N, Peries M, Dujols P, Bolloré K, Rénier W, Viljoen J, et al. Performance of two real-time PCR assays for hepatitis B Virus DNA Detection and quantitation. J Virol Methods. 2014 Jun. 3. Ouedraogo DE, Bollore K, Viljoen J, et al. Comparison of EBV DNA viral load in whole blood, plasma, B-cells and B-cell culture supernatant. J Med Virol. 2014 May. 4. Mange A, Tuaillon E, Viljoen J, et al. Elevated concentrations of milk β2-microglobulin is associated with increased risk of breastfeeding transmission of HIV-1 (Vertical Transmission Study). J Proteome Res. 2013 Dec 6. 5. Ouedraogo DE, Makinson A, ….Viljoen J, et al. Pivotal role of HIV and EBV replication in the long-term persistence of monoclonal gammopathy in patients on antiretroviral therapy. Blood. 2013 Oct 24. 6. Tanser F, Jones KG, Viljoen J, et al. Human Papillomavirus seropositivity and subsequent risk of HIV acquisition in rural South African women. Sex Transm Dis. 2013 Jul. 7. Ndirangu J, Viljoen J (co-first author), Bland RM, et al. Cell-Free (RNA) and Cell-Associated (DNA) HIV-1 and Postnatal Transmission through Breastfeeding. PLoS One. 2012. 8. Van de Perre P, Rubbo PA, Viljoen J, et al. HIV-1 reservoirs in breast milk and challenges to elimination of breast-feeding transmission of HIV-1. Science Translational Medicine. 2012 Jul 18. 9. Neveu D, Viljoen J (co-first author), Bland RM, et al. Cumulative exposure to cell-free HIV in breast-milk, rather than feeding pattern per se, identifies postnatally infected infants. Clin Infect Dis 2011 Mar.

description: 1. Field and laboratory evaluation of the Calypte® Aware™ HIV-1/2 OMT Rapid Test for the detection of antibodies to HIV-1/-2 in oral mucosal transudate, and the Calypte® Aware™ HIV-1/2 Urine Rapid Test for use on urine. 2. Laboratory evaluation of the Roche Combi® 4th generation ELISA as first line assay for the diagnosis of HIV-infection in adults in a reference laboratory. 3. Responsible for development and operational implementation of field and laboratory components of a provincial Influenza Surveillance System in conjunction with the National Influenza Surveillance Network. Optimisation of viral isolation (shell-vial, tube and egg inoculation) and PCR typing methodology in the laboratory. 4. Assist the provincial Avian Influenza Task Team in developing guidelines to facilitate implementation of the national Avian Influenza Preparedness Programme [Keynote address on Avian Influenza epidemiology at the 10th Annual Conference of the Rural Doctor's Association of Southern Africa (RuDASA), Empangeni, KwaZulu-Natal, 11 Aug 2006]. 5. Initiate, obtain funding, conduct and/or supervise research projects towards publication and/or higher degrees. 6. Teach undergraduate students (MBChB, BSc Med, Biomed Tech), postgraduate students (honours, masters, registrars), healthcare personnel (nursing staff) and medical practitioners (Continuing Professional Development). 7. Design and adapt laboratory testing algorithms in a cost-effective manner towards accreditation, quality assurance, health and safety. 8. Provide a clinical and laboratory consultation service to clinicans, scientists and technologists to facilitate an effective and efficient work flow and patient diagnosis. 9. Assist the provincial polio and measles surveillance arms of the Expanded Programme on Immunisation in South Africa (EPI SA).

description: Historically, this was the time period leading up to, and immediately prior to the national HIV Antiretroviral Treatment (ARV) Programme being launched by the South African Dept of Health, in or after 2004/5. Thus, in preparation for antiretroviral medication becoming available in our study area, we designed treatment trials aimed at informing on optimal management of ARVs in resource-limited settings. The Africa Centre is located in Somkhele, en route to Hlabisa, Umkhanyakude district, Zululand, in one of the areas worst-affected by the HIV/AIDS pandemic, and with some of the highest prevalence figures worldwide. Additional research include: 1. Supervision of anthropological masters' research project investigating the acceptability of male circumcision among the rural Zulu population in the region. [Scott BE, Weiss HA, Viljoen JI. The acceptability of male circumcision as an HIV intervention among a rural Zulu population, KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa. AIDS Care. 2005 Apr;17(3):304-13]. 2. Clinical Epidemiology: Responsible for the design, implementation and conduction of a variety of clinical research studies [acknowledgement: Jaffar S, et al. Antiretroviral treatment in resource-poor settings: public health research priorities. Trop Med Int Health. 2005 Apr;10(4):295-9]. 3. Clinical diagnosis of verbal autopsy reports to determine causes of death [acknowledgement: Hosegood V, et al. Levels and causes of adult mortality in rural South Africa: the impact of AIDS. AIDS. 2004 Mar 5;18(4):663-71].

description: 1. Diagnosis of infant HIV infection by p24-antigen detection [acknowledgement: van Gend CL, et al. Evaluation of the WHO clinical case definition for paediatric HIV infection in Bloemfontein, South Africa. J Trop Pediatr. 2003 Jun;49(3):143-7]. 2. Laboratory investigation into the serological presence of Hantavirus antibodies in rodents in South Africa. [Viljoen J, Oelofsen MJ, van der Ryst E, Vapalathi O, Lee PW. Hantavirus antibodies in rodents in South Africa. IXth International Congress on Infectious Diseases, Buenos Aires, Argentina, Apr 2000 (poster)]. 3. Primate study to evaluate the immunogenicity of human papillomavirus virus-like particles in baboons after oral immunisation; responsible for direct intra-gastric vaccination, specimen collection (throat swab, vaginal washes, blood collection) and viable lymphocyte separation, UFS Animal Research Centre (Dec 1998 – Oct 1999). 4. Comparison of MKC-442 (Emivirine) vs Abacavir, given with FTC-102 (Emtricitabine) and d4T to treatment-naïve HIV-infected patients (Aug 1999 - Mar 2001). 5. Comparison of two dosage regimens of MKC-442 (Emivirine), given with d4T and ddI to treatment-naïve HIV-infected patients (Dec 1998 - Mar 2001). 6. Comparison of once daily FTC-102 (Emtricitabine) to twice daily administered 3TC in HIV-1 infected patients in a 10-day dosing regimen (Aug - Oct 1998). 7. Investigation into the effect of IgX immunoglobulin on Cryptosporidial diarrhoea in HIV/AIDS patients (Sep 1997 - Dec 1998). 8. A randomised controlled clinical trial to investigate the effect of vitamin A on mother to child transmission of HIV-1 (Sep 1997 - Mar 2001).

description: Writer/Editor Consultant to Professor Nicholas J. White Prepared research proposals, progress reports and antimalarial drugs’ efficacy and safety reviews, including the following: 1) Primaquine safety review: Extensive review for WHO on primaquine safety focused on its use as a gametocytocide for falciparum treatment accompanying ACTs. Presented findings to WHO Evidence Review Group (ERG) which agreed on new recommendations for the use of primaquine, subsequently endorsed by the Malaria Policy Advisory Committee (MPAC) resulting in a primaquine policy update on October 2012 (WHO ERG meeting report and MPAC policy update available from session 5 at: http://www.who.int/malaria/mpac/sep2012/en/index.html). 2) Artemisin resistance research proposal: Coordinated preparation of successful bid to DFID to research artemisinin resistance in South East Asia (3 year grant totaling GBP 5.5 million). 3) Dihydroartemisinin-piperaquine safety review: Conducted literature review and summarized findings related to product safety of dihydroartemisinin-piperaquine safety for Chinese pharmaceutical company, for subsequent submission to WHO. 4) Pharmaceutical product development progress report: Summarized progress in development of a new antimalarial rectal formulation for the Wellcome Trust.

description: After initially setting up the laboratory of Dr. David Allis which was moving from U. Virginia to Rockefeller University and acting as the laboratory manager for 6 months, I conducted research in the field of chromatin biology and technicians and graduate students in the use of budding yeast as a tool to study chromatin-related processes. I generated different yeast point mutants in genes encoding histones and In collaboration with a Biotech company I used them to assay candidate antibodies for specificity of the antisera in detecting histone post-translational modifications. We successfully made and used one such antibody to histone H3 acetylation in lysine 56 to characterize this modification.

description: Therapeutic probiotics are promising agents for microbiome manipulation, and could be applied as a means to prevent or treat a variety of illnesses ranging from acute infections to chronic immune disease. Rational selection of such agents will aid in the expansion of safer treatment options for children. I have developed techniques that combine bacterial genetics, biochemistry and functional genomics to characterize probiotic anti-infective mediators generated by the model organism, Lactobacillus reuteri.

Manage a team of researchers to design and implement studies to evaluate the impact of a decade implementing HIV-related treatment and prevention interventions in Côte d’Ivoire. Build researchers capacity through mentoring. Provide support to the government of Côte d’Ivoire to plan surveillance activities. Prepare work plans, budgets and country operational plans. Ensure collaborative partnership with CDC and the government of Côte d'Ivoire.

description: Provides technical assistance on second generation HIV surveillance to FHI offices and National AIDS programs in Indonesia, Lao PDR, China, India, Pakistan, Papua New Guinea, and Nepal. Morineau provides training and technical assistance for surveillance planning, survey design, population size estimation, data analysis, interpretation of survey results, and modeling. Review international publications, abstracts and presentations from FHI country offices throughout Asia. Provide assistance for international trainings on surveillance and participate in international discussions aiming to develop standard methodologies for surveillance in concentrated HIV epidemics.

description: Provided technical assistance to the National AIDS programs in Indonesia, Cambodia and Laos for the second generation HIV surveillance system. Planned, designed and managed surveillance surveys, organized data collection process, analyzed data and produced national reports. Used data to model HIV epidemics. Provided interpretations of the analysis of the HIV/AIDS epidemic and evaluations of programs’ impact. Designed and conducted ad hoc surveys to: assess health facility readiness to deliver ART, evaluate the population size of most at risk groups, evaluate peer-education programs, and monitor quality of life among ART beneficiaries. Provided trainings and built capacity of national counterparts.

description: Spro Medical Products (Xiamen) Co., Ltd. was founded in 1998. For these years development, we set up Hong Kong and Canada offices and became one of the leading medical manufacturers in China. Our factory is located in Xiamen City, China, with 50,000 square meters plant area for manufacturing and storage. Our customers come from over 40 countries and areas, such as Japan, Taiwan Area, Italy, Germany and Australia. Our innovative Research & Development Department develops more than 100 varieties to satisfy all kinds of career needs. Our main products include mask, isolation gown, cap and shoes cover. And we also supply syringes and needles, such as plain lure, luerlock and syringe, infusion sets, hypodermic needles, sponge dressing, bandage, latex examination gloves and vinyl examination gloves. By adopting advanced technology, we were successfully certificated with ISO13485. Equipped with good resources, and relying on scientific management, we will provide our customers the best quality and high performance products. Our factory welcomes OEM and ODM orders.

We weave a multitude of advanced fibers including carbon, aramid, s-glass and high-molecular weight polyethylene. CFA is backed by 95 years of experience in the textile industry and has textile engineers and designers on staff who truly understand the principles of weaving. In addition to weaving the industry standard fabrics, at CFA we work with our clients to create specific fabrics to meet the individual needs of each of our clients. We have the ability to weave fabrics from 1 inch to nearly 87 inches in width and will help our customers to create custom constructions and even custom woven patterns. We have a thorough understanding of the various fabrication processes and procedures and work with our clients to create fabrics specific to these procedures. We also provide fabrics to pregreg facilities with quality that is simply second-to-none in the industry. Contact us today and let us show you how 95 years of weaving experience combined with unrivaled quality and exceptional customer service can make difference in your business.

description: Driftsansvar, logistik, lagerstyring, Lay-out, teknisk dokumentation og arbejdstegninger, medarbejderudvikling og -ansvar, indkøring af anlæg, driftsbelægning, tolerancer og opmåling, leverandørkontakt, ordrehåndtering, indkøb, jern- og metalerfaringkran og truck + læsning og losning, båndsavs-, svejse- og laserbetjening. I mit arbejde som gruppeleder har jeg beskæftiget mig med alt fra ordrehåndtering og logistik til medarbejderudvikling og kundekontakt. Jeg har en bred materialeforståelse og erfaring med 3D-print, kran, truck, industrilasere, skæreplottere, håndværktøj, universallasere, båndsave og CNC-fræsere, og har en generel forståelse af både håndværk og maskinel bearbejdning. Jeg har tegningsforståelse, samt uddannelse og erfaring med ISO-standarder og tolerancer. - opmåling af enmer - tolerancer på emner - indkøring af anlæg - Båndsav (fluen på væggen ved laser- og drejebænksindkøring) - medarbejderudvikling (MUS, løn, alm. udvikling og trivsel) - ansættelsessamtaler - logistik (fra A til Z) - ordrehåndtering (fra A til Z) - priskalkulation (bearbejdning af emner) - belægningstider (båndsav + ordrer) - planlægning af arbejdstider for medarbejdere - teknisk indkøb (industrimaskiner) - flow- og procesdiagrammer (optimering af layout) - Laserbearbejdning - Drejebænk (minimal erfaring) - Kran (travers) - Truck (alle slags) - kendskab til rør, stænger, plader, profiler, behandlede emner, - læsning og losning + fragtpapirer - mindre svejseopgaver - andre administrative opgaver

description: - Gerenciamento total da empresa. - Estruturação do departamento comercial - Aumento em 60% da produção da unidade - Reestruturação completa da empresa: - elaboração de novos traços de concreto - desenvolvimento de novos fornecedores de agregados e cimento - atualização do programa de gestão da usina - Modernização do modus operandi da empresa - Planejamento do faturamento da empresa. - Controle financeiro e estratégico da empresa - Responsável Técnico do concreto produzido. - General management of the company. - Structuring the commercial department - Total restructuring, as: - Development of new concrete mixtures - Development of new aggregate and cement suppliers - Update the plant management program - Company billing planning - Financial and strategic control of the branch - Technical Director of the produced concrete.

description: - Gerenciamento total da Regional São Paulo. - Controle e acompanhamento dos vendedores com análise geral de desempenho individual e das oportunidades trazidas pelos mesmos - Forte atuação em negociações com clientes, diretamente com seus proprietários. - Planejamento de faturamento da empresa. - Controle financeiro e estratégico da Regional - Responsável Técnico do concreto produzido. - Gerenciamento dos contratos de fornecimento de concreto nas obras. - Controle de análise de custos dos materiais constituintes do concreto, máquinas e equipamentos de centrais de concreto e caminhões betoneira. - Estabelecimento de territórios, cotas, planejamento de itinerários, controle de despesas e abertura de novos clientes. - Total Management of the São Paulo branch. - Takeover and monitoring of the salesmen with general analysis of individual performance, and the opportunities brought by the salesmen - High trading actuations with clients, directly with the company owners. - Planning the company billing. - Financial and strategical control of the branch - Technical responsible for the concrete produced. - Management of the concrete supply contracts for the constructions. - Controlling cost analysis of the constitutive materials of concrete, machines and equipment of concrete plants and concrete mixer trucks. - Setting up territory, cotes, itinerary planning, running costs control - Making new deals with customers

description: - Estabelecimento de territórios, cotas, planejamento de itinerários, controle de despesas e abertura de novos clientes para a melhoria da qualidade dos materiais empregados. - Suporte e atendimento a mais de 20 clientes - Estudos de novas tecnologias de concretos e de melhoria tecnológica dos concretos produzidos nas empresas. - Desenvolvimento de novos concretos e ensaios técnicos em concreteiras e empresas de pré-moldados. - Elaboração e acompanhamento do Plano Estratégico de Negócios, desenvolvendo estudos estratégicos, planos de negócios, estudos de viabilidade, portfólio de produtos, pesquisas de produtos e concorrência. - Establishing territory, quotes, route planning, costs control and getting new customers to improve the quality of the materials - Support and attendance for more than 20 clients - Study of the new concrete technologies, and the technical improvement of the concrete used at the concrete ready mixer companies. - Development of new concrete technologies and technical tests in concrete ready mixer companies and precast companies. - Elaborations and monitoring of the Strategic Business Plan, developing strategic studies, business plan, feasibility study, products portfolio, products and competition research.
